\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 1. F. carica} L., {\i Sp. Pl.} 1059 (1753). Spreading, deciduous shrub or small tree. Leaves 10-20 cm long and wide, usually palmately lobed, usually cordate at base, scabrid, sparsely hispid beneath. Syncarp 5-8 cm, pyriform, greenish- or brownish-violet. 2n = 26.{\i  Extensively cultivated and widely naturalized in S. Europe; perhaps native in the southern parts of the C. and E. Mediterranean region.} *Al *Bl *Co Cr *Ga Gr *Hs It *Ju Sa Si *Tu [Au Az Br Cz He Hu Lu Rs(K)]. ({\i S.W. Asia}.)
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 Many cultivars exist and the wild plant (var. {\i caprificus} Risso) also shows considerable variability. The syncarps (Figs) are eaten both fresh and dried.
\par

